"# Appendix D — Tone Table

A quick-lookup table of the notes used across the book, in equal
temperament with A4 = 440 Hz. Numbers are rounded to the nearest
hundredth of a Hertz. When a chapter says 'play middle C', this table
is what middle C sounds like in frequency.

---

## Octave 4 (middle range)

  C4  = 261.63 Hz
  C#4 = 277.18 Hz
  D4  = 293.66 Hz
  D#4 = 311.13 Hz
  E4  = 329.63 Hz
  F4  = 349.23 Hz
  F#4 = 369.99 Hz
  G4  = 392.00 Hz
  G#4 = 415.30 Hz
  A4  = 440.00 Hz   ← the reference pitch
  A#4 = 466.16 Hz
  B4  = 493.88 Hz

## Octave 3 (an octave below)

  C3  = 130.81 Hz
  D3  = 146.83 Hz
  E3  = 164.81 Hz
  F3  = 174.61 Hz
  G3  = 196.00 Hz
  A3  = 220.00 Hz
  B3  = 246.94 Hz

## Octave 5 (an octave above)

  C5  = 523.25 Hz
  D5  = 587.33 Hz
  E5  = 659.26 Hz
  F5  = 698.46 Hz
  G5  = 783.99 Hz
  A5  = 880.00 Hz
  B5  = 987.77 Hz

## Rule of doubling

Each octave up doubles the frequency. Each octave down halves it.
A0 = 27.5 Hz. A8 = 7040 Hz. Both are edge notes on a piano.

## Getting any note from any other note

Multiply by 2^(n/12) to go up n semitones. Divide to go down. That is
equal temperament in one sentence.

## The consonant intervals (why chords sound like chords)

  unison       — ratio 1:1  (same note)
  octave       — ratio 2:1
  perfect 5th  — ratio 3:2  (close in equal temperament)
  perfect 4th  — ratio 4:3
  major 3rd    — ratio 5:4
  minor 3rd    — ratio 6:5

Chapter 2 explains why simple ratios sound good — the partials line
up. This appendix is just the lookup.

---

If a chapter asks for a note and you cannot recall the Hz, come here.
That is the entire purpose.")
